description.text:
This is a variant of the video Shiftingthebeamenteringawhisperingga... using a chirp, which is a wave of linearly increasing oscillation frequency. 
Recently, this channel featured several videos showing light being approximately trapped between two confocal parabolic reflectors, that were suggested by viewer Andr Pscherer. 
This video is another suggestion by Andr, based on the post https://physics.stackexchange.com/que... , asking whether light can be trapped in an optical fiber, owing to total internal refraction. The refracting region consists here of two half-disc of slightly different radius, so that one can attach an optical fiber to the larger half-disc. The fiber has been coated by a reflecting layer to avoid leakage of light. The refractive index of the discs and fiber, relative to the exterior of the discs, is equal to 2.5. A linear wave is excited in the fiber by an oscillating boundary condition. Although the wave height part of the simulation shows that part of the waves do escape the discs, the energy part shows that the escaping waves contain a relatively small fraction of the total energy.
This video has two parts, showing the same simulation with two different color gradients.
Wave height: 0:00
Wave energy 1:32
In part 1, the  color hue depends on the wave height.  In part 2, it depends on the wave energy, averaged over a time window. The boundary conditions are absorbing. 
The fact that the beam of light seems to curve in the second part is due to a combination of interference and the color gradient, which does not show waves of low energy. 

Render time: 36 minutes 16 seconds
Compression: crf 25
ffmpeg option: noise=alls=10:allf=t+u
Color scheme: Part 1 - Viridis by Nathaniel J. Smith, Stefan van der Walt and Eric Firing
Part 2 - Inferno by Nathaniel J. Smith and Stefan van der Walt
https://github.com/BIDS/colormap

Music: "Balearic Slide" by Jeremy Black@TRUEBLUEMUSICLTD

See also 
https://images.math.cnrs.fr/des-ondes... for more explanations (in French) on  a few previous simulations of wave equations. 

The simulation solves the wave equation by discretization. The algorithm is adapted from the paper https://hplgit.github.io/fdm-book/doc... 
C code: https://github.com/nilsberglund-orlea...
https://www.idpoisson.fr/berglund/sof...
Many thanks to Marco Mancini and Julian Kauth for helping me to accelerate my code!
